[[Women's suffrage]] has been achieved at various times in various countries throughout the world. In many countries women's suffrage was granted before [[universal suffrage]], so women (and men) from certain classes or [[Race (classification of human beings)|races]] were still unable to vote, while some granted it to both sexes at the same time.

The timeline below lists years when women's suffrage was enacted in various places. In many cases the first voting took place in a subsequent year.

[[New Zealand]] in 1893 is often said to be the [[Women's suffrage in New Zealand|first country in the world to give women the right to vote]].  A contestant for being the first independent nation to grant women the right to vote would be [[Sweden]], where conditional woman suffrage was granted during the [[age of liberty]] between 1718 and 1771, when taxpaying women listed in their guilds as professionals were allowed to vote<ref name="Karlsson-Sjögreen 1866">* Åsa Karlsson-Sjögren: ''"Männen, kvinnorna och rösträtten : medborgarskap och representation 1723–1866"'' (Men, women and the vote: citizenship and representation 1723–1866) (in Swedish)</ref>

''Disclaimer: This timeline reflects a vast amount of information from the women's suffrage movement throughout the globe. In many cases, countries passed various laws which progressively gave women the right to vote. Many countries may appear on the list more than once because restrictions on suffrage were only lifted slowly. This list only states the right to vote; for other rights, see [[Timeline of women's rights (other than voting)]].''
[[File:Suffrage parade-New York City-May 6 1912.jpg|thumb|400px|right|Suffrage parade, New York City, May 6, 1912.]]

== 18th century ==
* '''1718'''
** {{flag|Sweden}} Female taxpaying members of city [[guild]]s are allowed to vote in local elections (rescinded in 1758) and national elections (rescinded in the new constitution of 1771).<ref name="Karlsson-Sjögreen 1866" />
* '''1755'''
** {{flagicon|Corsica}} [[Corsican Republic|Corsica]] (rescinded upon annexation by France in 1769){{Citation needed|date=September 2009}}
* '''1756–1778'''
** {{flagicon|Massachusetts}} [[Province of Massachusetts Bay]], [[Lydia Taft]], [[Uxbridge, Massachusetts]] [[town meeting]]
* '''1776'''
** {{flag|New Jersey}} (rescinded in 1807)

== 19th century ==
* '''1838'''
** {{flag|Pitcairn Islands}}
* '''1861'''
** {{flag|South Australia}} (Only property-owning women for local elections, universal franchise in 1894)
* '''1862'''
** {{flag|Sweden}} (only in local elections, votes graded after taxation, universal franchise in 1919, which went into effect at the 1921 elections)<ref name="jstor.org">[http://www.jstor.org/pss/1946097 P. Orman Ray: Woman Suffrage in Foreign Countries. The American Political Science Review. Vol. 12, No. 3 (Aug., 1918), pp. 469-474 ]</ref>
*'''1863'''
** {{flagicon|Finland}} The [[Grand Duchy of Finland|Grand Principality of Finland]] was part of the Russian Empire from 1809 to 1917 and enjoyed a high degree of [[autonomy]]. In 1863, taxpaying women were granted municipal suffrage in the country side, and in 1872, the same reform was given to the cities<ref name="jstor.org"/>
* '''1864'''
** {{flagicon|Victoria}} Women in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria, Australia]] were unintentionally enfranchised by the ''Electoral Act'' (1863), and proceeded to vote in the following year's elections. The Act was amended in 1865 to correct the error.<ref>[http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/about/the-history-of-parliament/women-in-parliament Women in Parliament - Parliament of Victoria<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
**{{flagicon|Bohemia}} In the former [[Kingdom of Bohemia]], taxpaying women and women in "learned professions" were allowed to vote by proxy and made eligible to the legislative body in 1864.<ref name="jstor.org"/>
* '''1869'''
** {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] (only in local elections, universal franchise in 1928)
* '''1869–1920'''
** {{flagicon|Wyoming}} [[US state|States]] and territories of the USA, progressively, starting with the [[Wyoming Territory]] in 1869 and the [[Utah Territory]] in 1870, though the latter was repealed by the [[Edmunds-Tucker Act]] in 1887. [[Wyoming]] acquired statehood in 1890 ([[Utah]] in 1896), allowing women to cast votes in federal elections. The United States as a whole acquired women's suffrage in 1920 (see below) through the [[Nineteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]]; voting qualifications in the U.S., even in federal elections, are set by the states, and this amendment prohibited states from discriminating on the basis of sex.
[[File:DSCN5264 wyomingcapitolmorrisstatue e.jpg|200px|right|thumb|Statue of [[Esther Hobart Morris]] in front of the [[Wyoming State Capitol]]]]
*'''1870'''
**{{flagicon|Utah}}[[Utah Territory]]
*'''1872'''
** {{flagicon|Finland}} [[Grand Duchy of Finland|Grand Principality of Finland]] was part of the Russian Empire from 1809 to 1917 and enjoyed a high degree of [[autonomy]]. In 1872, taxpaying women were granted municipal suffrage in the cities<ref name="jstor.org"/>
* '''1881'''
** {{flag|Isle of Man}} (only property-owners until 1913, universal franchise in 1919.)
* '''1884'''
** {{flag|Canada|1868}} Widows and spinsters granted the right to vote within municipalities in [[Ontario]] (later to other provinces).<ref>[http://faculty.marianopolis.edu/c.belanger/quebechistory/encyclopedia/Canada-WomensVote-WomenSuffrage.htm Canada-WomensVote-WomenSuffrage]</ref>
* '''1889'''
** {{flagicon image|Flag of Franceville.svg}} [[Franceville, New Hebrides|Franceville]] grants universal suffrage.<ref>"Wee, Small Republics: A Few Examples of Popular Government," ''Hawaiian Gazette'', Nov 1, 1895, p 1</ref> Loses self-rule within months.
* '''1893'''
** {{flag|Colorado}}
** {{flag|New Zealand}} September 19 (including [[Māori people|Maori]] women; although women were barred from standing for election until 1919)
** {{flag|Cook Islands}}
* '''1894'''
** {{flag|South Australia}} grants universal suffrage, extending the franchise to all women (property-owners could vote in local elections from 1861), the first in Australia to do so. Women are also granted the right to stand for parliament, making South Australia the first in the world to do so.
** {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] extends right to vote in local elections to married women.
* '''1896'''
** {{flag|Idaho}}
* '''1899'''
** {{flag|Western Australia}}

== 20th century ==
=== 1900s ===
* '''1902'''
** {{flagicon|Australia}} [[Australia|Commonwealth of Australia]] (The [[Constitution of Australia|Australian Constitution]] gave the federal franchise to all persons allowed to vote for the lower house in each state unless the [[Parliament of Australia|Commonwealth Parliament]] stipulated otherwise. Thus, [[South Australia]]n and Western Australian women could vote in the [[Australian general election, 1901|first federal election in 1901]]. During the first Parliament, the Commonwealth passed legislation extending federal franchise to non-Aboriginal women in all states.)
** {{flag|New South Wales}}
* '''1903'''
** {{flag|Tasmania}}
* '''1905'''
** {{flag|Queensland}}
* '''1906'''
** {{flagicon|Finland}} The [[Grand Duchy of Finland|Grand Principality of Finland]] was the first country to have universal suffrage. First country to give the right to vote and right to stand for elections to everyone of age regardless of wealth, race or social class.[http://www.aanioikeus.fi/en/articles/strike.htm]
** {{flag|New Hebrides}} Perhaps inspired by the Franceville experiment, the [[History_of_Vanuatu#Condominium|Anglo-French Condominium of the New Hebrides]] granted women the right to vote in municipal elections and to serve on elected municipal councils. (These rights applied only to British, French, and other colonists, not to indigenous islanders.)<ref>Bourdiol, Julien (1908), ''Condition internationale des Nouvelles-Hebrides'', p 106</ref>
[[File:Women suffrage cartoon.png|right|thumb|The argument over women's rights in Victoria was lampooned in this ''Melbourne Punch'' cartoon of 1887]]
* '''1908'''
** {{flag|Denmark}} (only in local elections)
** {{flag|Victoria}}

